(window.webpackJsonp=window.webpackJsonp||[]).push([[5],{97:function(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('{"metadata":{"timed":true,"story ID":"39e000d8-5a1a-4502-9c56-adca33e5ff2c","title":{"_default":"PCSD_004_Sandra_Gilyard_3-5-2022"},"media":{"audio":"","video":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NHgmd0UgD7k"},"languages":[],"date_created":"","date_uploaded":"2/28/2025","source":{"_default":""},"description":"","genre":"","author":"","glosser":"","speakers":[],"xml_file_name":"PCSD_004_Sandra_Gilyard_3-5-2022.eaf","source_filetype":"ELAN","tier IDs":{"Speaker 2":{"subdivided":false},"Speaker 3":{"subdivided":false}},"speaker IDs":{"S1":{"tier":"Speaker 2"},"S2":{"tier":"Speaker 3"}}},"sentences":[{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":6000,"end_time_ms":19000,"num_slots":1,"text":"All right. So my name is Laura Tema. I\'m here with the Samuel Proctor Oral History Program on March 5th in pco, Florida. And I\'m here with Miss","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":19000,"end_time_ms":21000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Sandra Gillard.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":21000,"end_time_ms":23000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Would you mind spelling the last name?","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":23000,"end_time_ms":27000,"num_slots":1,"text":"G-I-L-Y-A-R-E. Gillard.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":27000,"end_time_ms":36000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Okay, awesome. And, um, so we will just start out with where you were born and, um, when","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":36000,"end_time_ms":69000,"num_slots":1,"text":"All righty. I was conceived in San Mateo, Florida, but I was born in Neptune, New Jersey. Oh. How that came to be is my parents were migrant workers. Our home has always been in San Mateo, but in the summer my family would go up and harvest the potatoes and my parents would go on and pick apples in New Jersey. And while I was born in 1953, October the 30th, 1953, a day before Halloween. So I\'m a treat and not a trick.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":69000,"end_time_ms":76000,"num_slots":1,"text":"<laugh>, I love that semester. I love that. And did you grow up in, um, New Jersey or,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":76000,"end_time_ms":84000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Oh, no, no, no. Oh, okay. I grew up in San Mateo in Florida. I bet I migrant workers mean you go up, you harvest the crops, and you come back home. They come","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":84000,"end_time_ms":85000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Back. All right. Yes.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":85000,"end_time_ms":108000,"num_slots":1,"text":"So I\'ve, I\'ve always gone to school in Putnam County from first grade on, uh, back then school would start after Labor Day, so we would stay up and work and then my grandparents would bring us home and we would start school, or we would come back from school maybe three weeks after school had started. When, when we finished the crops, when my parents finished them.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":108000,"end_time_ms":119000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Okay. Um, and so you would stay here and in Palka. And where did you San Mattia. San Mattia? Yes. And where did you go to school?","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":119000,"end_time_ms":142000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Alright, in elementary I went to East Palka Elementary and back then, uh, elementary went from first grade to sixth grade. And then Palka, well, central Academy High went from seven to 12. So when we would graduate sixth grade, well be promoted from sixth grade, we would then come to Palka.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":142000,"end_time_ms":149000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And grade seven through 12 at Central Academy High. Okay. We had no middle school then.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":149000,"end_time_ms":154000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And can you describe the community around here a little bit","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":154000,"end_time_ms":159000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Now? You mean the community where I grew up? Or the community where the school is located?","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":159000,"end_time_ms":161000,"num_slots":1,"text":"The community where you grew up.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":161000,"end_time_ms":239000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Alright. Um, family oriented, Christian community. Um, one or two telephones in the whole community. But if you did something, uh, on one street before you got home, it was already there. Everybody knew it. Uh, the village truly raised the child. Uh, parents listened to what other parents had to say, and it was no question about it. If Miss so and so say you did it, you may as well have, because that\'s the way it was back then. Uh, close knit. There were two black churches. One was a Methodist, which is where I attended. It was new be African Methodist Episcopal Church. The other one was Second Mount tab Missionary Baptist. So it was a Baptist church and, uh, an a ME church or Methodist Church. And what they did, first and third Sunday was at my church. Second and fourth Sunday was at the Baptist Church. So we went to church around, I mean, around the clock. And Reverend Wright years ago when my grandfather passed at his, at his homegrown celebration, uh, Reverend Wright simply said, Jim Hostly, you didn\'t know whether he was Methodist a Baptist, because that\'s the way we grew up. Everybody took care of everybody.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":239000,"end_time_ms":241000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Yeah. And","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":241000,"end_time_ms":242000,"num_slots":1,"text":"It was great.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":242000,"end_time_ms":258000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Um, <laugh>, I\'m sorry, but do you mind really quickly if I grab that from you for a second? I think it accidentally turned off and because I don\'t, I just noticed that there\'s no blue. I\'m so sorry to interrupt you.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":258000,"end_time_ms":259000,"num_slots":1,"text":"So nothing is record?","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":259000,"end_time_ms":272000,"num_slots":1,"text":"No, it, it was recording. Oh, okay. Um, but now reclip that, and then it\'ll, lemme just put it here. It\'ll make the sound a little bit better Now. For some reason, the blue wasn\'t flashing and that,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":272000,"end_time_ms":274000,"num_slots":1,"text":"See if it\'s flashing now. Yeah,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":274000,"end_time_ms":282000,"num_slots":1,"text":"I see it. So it\'s all good there. Okay. Okay. And so, um, describe a little bit more about how you were connected to the church and,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":282000,"end_time_ms":336000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Um, that I was totally connected because my grandfather was, uh, a steward in my church. That\'s the right hand man to, to the pastor. Uh, and so we went to Sunday school every Sunday. We went to church every Sunday, first and third at mine, second and fourth down at second Mount table. Uh, the only way you got to stay home from church was you were sick. Just like with school, if, if I stayed home from school, when the school students got in, I didn\'t get to go out and play that day if I was supposed to be sick, I was sick until the next day that I went to school and came home. So, so that\'s the way it was. Uh, the c community, like I said, was close knit. Uh, the different churches would have like a fish fry to raise money to do things that the church needed to be done.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":336000,"end_time_ms":402000,"num_slots":1,"text":"They would make homemade ice cream at Santa Grace Brown, two doors down from us, uh, would do that. I mean, Saturdays, after you took care of your chores, raking the yard, washing the clothes, hanging them out. We didn\'t have dryers hanging those clothes out on the line for them to dry. Then the kids would play in the community. It was just, it was just close knit. And like I said earlier, every parent, every adult took care of the children in that community. If they saw you doing something that was wrong, either they would chastise you and tell you, uh, and tell your parents and you got another, or they would call and make sure your parents took care of it. So it, they just looked out for each other. The church did it and the community, because honestly, the community was the church. I can remember, and this is the final thing I\'m gonna say, \'cause I know you got other people I can remember you, you went to Sunday school, you went to church and after church they would play softball. Yes. Everybody would come out and play softball. But if you didn\'t go to church,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":402000,"end_time_ms":404000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Couldn\'t play. Yeah. That\'s it.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":404000,"end_time_ms":421000,"num_slots":1,"text":"<laugh>. That\'s it. You, so you couldn\'t fake anything. If you wanted to be a part of the good things that were happening, they would play teams in East Bca, orange Mills, uh, Pomona Park had a team, and we would go and watch the adults play. It was, it was, it was great. Poor, but we didn\'t know it.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":421000,"end_time_ms":422000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Yeah. And I\'m","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":422000,"end_time_ms":424000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Sure nobody told us we were poor","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":424000,"end_time_ms":437000,"num_slots":1,"text":"<laugh>. I\'m sure you wouldn\'t even wanna miss out, so you wouldn\'t even wanna Yes, yes. Yeah. So, and going back a little bit to just more your family, um, what was your family like, siblings? Uh,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":437000,"end_time_ms":491000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Yeah. Uh, my, my, it was my mother and father. We were reared in a three bedroom wooden frame home. And it still stands today, a niece lives there right across the street from me. I built across the street from, from my family home. It was my mother and father. My oldest sister, Hazel had gotten married and she had three children. Well, she died at age 21 of a brain aneurysm. Wow. And she left three babies. The baby was six months old. Fred, Rick, Frederick, we some call him Fred, some call him Rick. But he was six months old. And Pokey the oldest, he was three, three or four. When, when their mother died, my mother reared all of them. So in that three bedroom house, there were about 12 people. The boys had a room, the girls had a room with bunk beds or the full size bed.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":491000,"end_time_ms":533000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And my mother and father. But we never went to bed hungry. We may not have had what others were eating, but we never went to bed hungry. And my granddad, he was a, what we call a contractor. He actually got the jobs for the cabbages, uh, cucumbers. He did potatoes and Hastings. And what he would do when, when he would come home, he would leave a cabbage down the brick road to the Gibson\'s home. He would drop off some potatoes to somebody else\'s home. So whatever people were working in, in that community, they would drop some of it off to others\' homes. So we,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":533000,"end_time_ms":535000,"num_slots":1,"text":"It\'s just some big sense of community.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":535000,"end_time_ms":541000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Yes, very much so. In every letter in the word we were community.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":541000,"end_time_ms":550000,"num_slots":1,"text":"That\'s amazing. Yes. And within your family, did, uh, what did your parents think of education and what did they emphasize with education?","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":550000,"end_time_ms":610000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Yes. Education was very, very important. Even though we were migrant workers, education was important. My grandfather that I told you about, his daughter, not my mother, but my mother\'s sister, she has a PhD. She retired from East Carolina University in Greenville, North Carolina. Mm-hmm <affirmative>. Um, when we would go upstate, like I told you, and harvest the potatoes, my daddy, during that time, my granddaddy did it. Those that were going to school, you were coming home and go to school, they would bring home the children and my parents would still working the apples. Or when we got older and my father took over, my grandfather was deceased, my daddy took over, I would leave, uh, them in, in New Jersey and I would catch the train home. Or one year they save up enough and got me an old car, drove that home. But every summer I would go up and work.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":610000,"end_time_ms":663000,"num_slots":1,"text":"When it was time for me to come back to a and m to college, I came. So I did it. My sister Regina did it. Both of us retired from the Putnam County School District as administrator. She retired as a principal. I retired down at the district office. Now I\'m on the school board. Um, my, um, niece Debbie, she was the younger, she\'s much younger than I am. She\'s like 58 or something. But anyway, long story short, my granddad, I mean, my father would send her back. When it was time for her to come to school, she went to East Carolina where my aunt was the professor. And now she is a pa. So they pushed education, well, number one, they pushed religion. I mean, not religion, Christianity. Mm-hmm <affirmative>. A love of Christ. And then education. \'cause they believed those things made the difference","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":663000,"end_time_ms":666000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And stuff. So your, all your siblings went to university","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":666000,"end_time_ms":693000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And not all, not all, but they, they got decent jobs. My brother Larry, he went, uh, for two years and then he got married and, and, and didn\'t go back. My oldest brother, uh, he never went. Uh, my baby brother didn\'t. But the ones, the key is the ones that wanted to go went, yes, my daddy. They made a way Yes. For them to go. Yes. And hard. But they made a way Yeah. Sacrificed. But they made a way. Yeah.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":693000,"end_time_ms":696000,"num_slots":1,"text":"I\'m sure they had to work very hard to","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":696000,"end_time_ms":702000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Yeah, very hard. And sacrifice and pray. Mm-hmm. Yeah. And cry and do whatever, <laugh>. But thank God.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":702000,"end_time_ms":707000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Yeah. And, uh, as a child, what was your experience with education?","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":707000,"end_time_ms":754000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Always wanted to go to school. Uh, again, the connection of church. One time I honestly thought I wanted to be a doctor, but in retrospect, I knew it was a selfish reason. Looked like they were the people that had it made. They, you know, that was the life I wanted to live. Yeah. But I couldn\'t stand the sight of blood almost passed out <laugh>. So I knew then, but in Sunday school when the teacher wasn\'t there, I would always want to teach. I would always want to teach. And I started teaching in Sunday school and then became superintendent of the Sunday school as I went, got older. Wow. And, and I became a teacher. I taught for 17 years right here in Putnam County. So it was that, you know, seeing the adults doing it and the joy they got from it.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":754000,"end_time_ms":759000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Mm-hmm <affirmative>. Yeah. And, uh, remind me of the elementary school that you went","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":759000,"end_time_ms":761000,"num_slots":1,"text":"To. East Palka, east Elementary School.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":761000,"end_time_ms":764000,"num_slots":1,"text":"How was that, uh, experience for you? Uh,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":764000,"end_time_ms":822000,"num_slots":1,"text":"It was, it was great. The only, uh, well, it it was great. It truly was great. Uh, the, the thing I told the kids over at Beasley was when we would get back late from upstate, and you would go into your classroom, whatever grade level you were in, and they would not test you necessarily, but they would put you in group three. There were three groups, red Bird, blue Birds, and Blackbird. And you started out as a Blackbird, which is the lowest group. That\'s the way it was. And so you would have to prove yourself. And, and I just got a joy outta showing them, Hey, I can probably read better than you. But anyway, what they didn\'t realize all those farmers and, and got together. We had schools from the time we left here. We were in, we called it summer school, but we were in school learning bible verses learning to read and do, do arithmetic. Back in the day it was called arithmetic. But hey, we never stopped learning time.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":822000,"end_time_ms":829000,"num_slots":1,"text":"So during the summers, did you go through a formalized, like education or was it just you guys pursuing your","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":829000,"end_time_ms":865000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Own? No, it was, it, there were, they were people from the church, volunteers. Some were teachers, but they were members of that church. They were the ones that were instructing. Then in Virginia, I had gotten older, so I was working then in the fields. But the younger ones actually got to go to Mack, uh, elementary school during the summer because they would actually take the migrant children and teach them, take \'em on field trips. I mean, it, you know, it, it was as good as could be.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":865000,"end_time_ms":868000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And then going on the middle and high school, um,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":868000,"end_time_ms":869000,"num_slots":1,"text":"No middle school.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":869000,"end_time_ms":871000,"num_slots":1,"text":"How high school? So elementary to high school,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":871000,"end_time_ms":875000,"num_slots":1,"text":"High school, right. Seven, seven to 12 was Central Academy.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":875000,"end_time_ms":877000,"num_slots":1,"text":"How was, how was Central Academy?","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":877000,"end_time_ms":936000,"num_slots":1,"text":"It was, it was, okay. Um, the difference being at East Malacca Elementary School, I knew all those kids because anyone that didn\'t live across the bridge, the Memorial Bridge up here, anybody that didn\'t live across the bridge, you automatically went to East Flac Elementary School. So I knew those students. But when I got here in Palka at, at, it was kinda, wow, all of these people, you know, I\'m not, you know, I\'m big brothers and football games, Uhhuh and dances and \'cause as a, when you got to ninth grade, now, seventh, eighth grade, they didn\'t have a dance. But when you got in ninth grade, they had what they called the freshman ball. Sophomores had the sophomore dance and then junior, senior prom. So those were things, uh, I hadn\'t been exposed to. And, and, and seeing and meeting new people and seeing so many in one place. But,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":936000,"end_time_ms":940000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And were you there while the desegregation efforts were going on?","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":940000,"end_time_ms":970000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Yes. First they sent in the teachers, a few white teachers came to, uh, central Academy. And then the next year we were, uh, zoned. And, and we had to go to the, uh, what we called the white school. It was Palka High then, but they changed the name to, uh, it was Palka Centerra and Palka South. That was where I went. Okay.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":970000,"end_time_ms":973000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Yes. So you were at Palka South, alright. Yes. Mm-hmm <affirmative>.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":973000,"end_time_ms":976000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And because I lived across the river.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":976000,"end_time_ms":981000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And Do you remember what, like, the racial makeup of the, the school was?","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":981000,"end_time_ms":1036000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Oh, oh, most definitely. The blacks were the minority. I mean, in a cl I can remember being fourth period, that\'s your lunch period. And I was the only black in, in, uh, it was, uh, American government. And that was supposed to be the honor class. And I was so uncomfortable. I did not like it. You know, I guess I could have been friendlier. I wasn\'t mean or anything, but I didn\'t force myself in or on anybody. And I would just sit there lunch. It was, it was miserable. And I finally got my schedule changed. Mm-hmm <affirmative>. I mean, you know. Yeah. Nobody made an effort to come toward me. And I, you know, and I just, it just wasn\'t good. It just wasn\'t good. Yeah. It, because I was in a position I had not asked to be in.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":1036000,"end_time_ms":1041000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Yeah. And Palka High was grades. Um,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1041000,"end_time_ms":1046000,"num_slots":1,"text":"What Then they had a middle school. So it was nine to 12. Okay. Nine to 12.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":1046000,"end_time_ms":1047000,"num_slots":1,"text":"So you went from nine to 12?","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1047000,"end_time_ms":1099000,"num_slots":1,"text":"No, no, no. Integration didn\'t hit me until my junior and senior year. I went my last two years. Oh, wow. Yes. Yeah. Yeah. That was, and that makes even worse. So worse. I, I, I really didn\'t want to, but I had no other choice. Yeah. I mean, what could I do? Yeah. I mean, and I knew I wanted to go to school, so I had to make the best of, of what was there and what was there. Was Palka South. The only way I could have gone to Palka Central would be to get somebody to drive me over here. My parents, if we had a car during that time, couldn\'t afford that because they were working. And so I couldn\'t live with relatives because they had house a house full of children in order to go to Central. Yeah. Because Central was predominantly black. Mm-hmm <affirmative>. South was predominantly white. Yeah.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":1099000,"end_time_ms":1107000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And, um, did you have any teachers or anything that you felt connected to anybody that reached out to help at all?","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1107000,"end_time_ms":1166000,"num_slots":1,"text":"The only the, the teacher that I would would say stand out in my mind, out of, out of the white teachers for integration would be Maj Butlin. She was the, uh, social studies teacher. She taught history. And, uh, you know, she would teach and we would listen and she would test. And my schools would be. And so I guess she connected with me that way. And I can remember one time she had, during that time, teachers could actually go to the restroom and not have anybody in the room, and you did what you were supposed to do. And so she kind of said, I\'m in charge. And, and I can recall helping others \'cause that\'s what I do. And it was a test. But yes, I helped others that was struggling. But I would say she was the one that reached out. Um, I may have left an impression on our, trying to think, what was his title?","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1166000,"end_time_ms":1239000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Uh, I can\'t remember his name. He taught, uh, it was acting, but it, but it had a name. The class had a name Mr. Mitchell. He was the teacher. And you would have to get your partner and get a little, uh, a little skit out of a play. Well get a little portion of a play and you and a partner would have to recite it. And he was kind of taken back as to how I could remember the part and put myself into it. And so I guess he kind remembered me. \'cause I can remember one day, you, you know, how you with your friends and you don\'t know an adult is behind you. And I said a bad word. And he told me he was disappointed and didn\'t believe that I would. And that thing, it, it got to me. Yeah. Disappointed for him to even say, \'cause he could have said care less. But he said he thought, and he, he was disappointed. So I spent the rest of that. We had him for a semester trying to make up and show him that, hey, it was one of those things and it won\'t happen again. But I can remember that.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":1239000,"end_time_ms":1241000,"num_slots":1,"text":"So there were no black teachers at","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1241000,"end_time_ms":1255000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Black Science? Yes, there were some black teachers there. But see, I knew them from, from, from, uh, ca uh, Ms. Medlock, she taught math. Of course, I got along great with her. She liked me, I liked her, you know. Yeah.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":1255000,"end_time_ms":1258000,"num_slots":1,"text":"But they were also the minority in the education,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1258000,"end_time_ms":1300000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Right? Right. Yes. As a matter of fact, Mrs. Medlock is the only one I can remember. Uh, Mr. Green, he was an assistant principal. Joe Green, he was an assistant principal, and I can remember him. Anyway, it was his wife that actually hired me. He was still living. She hired me and gave me my first job as a teacher. So. Oh, wow. So I can I, but as far as him having a connection with me, I guess you could say yes, but it wasn\'t, it\'s like he saw me. He, he knew, I guess my potential, so to speak, and sort of kept just","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":1300000,"end_time_ms":1301000,"num_slots":1,"text":"An acquaintance. Yeah.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1301000,"end_time_ms":1302000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Yeah.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":1302000,"end_time_ms":1313000,"num_slots":1,"text":"So when you switched from Central Academy to Palatka South, did you notice differences in, you know, resources and","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1313000,"end_time_ms":1314000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Now you know it?","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":1314000,"end_time_ms":1317000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Yeah. Yeah. <laugh>,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1317000,"end_time_ms":1331000,"num_slots":1,"text":"I mean, I, from, from the equipment and the classroom to the books being <laugh> fairly new. Yes. I, I\'d be lying if I, if I, if I said I didn\'t mm-hmm <affirmative>. Yes.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":1331000,"end_time_ms":1341000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And in Palatka High, Palatka South, um, was there any clubs or organizations or any teams that you","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1341000,"end_time_ms":1398000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Joined or, no, I, I didn\'t join. You didn\'t join? Um, number one because I, I wouldn\'t have, they\'re all after school pretty much. And you would have to have transportation. And because my parents worked, both parents worked. My mom would be in the field cutting potatoes. My dad was working with George Curry, taking care of the fruit for the fruit market that used to be open 24 7. So, um, that\'s why I, one of the things I hated was when we left Central Academy, I was on the basketball team because my mother had played on Lefty Turner\'s championship team. They were state champs back in 40 something. Anyway, so I played basketball. Well, the coach, Ms. Vacia Tompkins would drive us home, otherwise we couldn\'t play. Yeah. She would load us up in her car and after practice, take us home after games take us home.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":1398000,"end_time_ms":1400000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Yeah. So there wasn\'t the same,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1400000,"end_time_ms":1401000,"num_slots":1,"text":"The opportunity as","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":1401000,"end_time_ms":1402000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Black","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1402000,"end_time_ms":1410000,"num_slots":1,"text":"South? No. And, and a lot of the clubs were already formed. And I mean, you knew it entered, you","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":1410000,"end_time_ms":1411000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Entered in 11th and","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1411000,"end_time_ms":1450000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Yes. You, I mean, you knew it. You, I\'m not gonna call \'em cliques, but everybody had their groups already. And there were a few blacks that they would allow in, but most of them that were in were the ones that went prior to desegregation. They went when there was a choice or a chance to go, I went when we were told we had to go. Yeah. So a few of them got in. I can remember Veronica Mavery being a brave at, and one or two others. They stuck in my opinion, I feel like put here, there, but they had already established themselves.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":1450000,"end_time_ms":1451000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Yeah.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1451000,"end_time_ms":1453000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And so I didn\'t, I didn\'t worry about","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":1453000,"end_time_ms":1459000,"num_slots":1,"text":"It. Yeah. It\'s hard to come in when things are already so concrete. Yeah.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1459000,"end_time_ms":1470000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Pretty much. And then even if I got in with something, how would I get back and forth Uhhuh? So, you know, it is, it, it was what it was <laugh>. Yeah.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":1470000,"end_time_ms":1481000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And when you first came in, or when the zoning first happened, how was it received among families within plaque ca South and how was it received?","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1481000,"end_time_ms":1536000,"num_slots":1,"text":"South in San Mateo, I know there was a lot of concern. Parents were, were very much so concerned. I can remember an incident that happened on the bus. Uh, we were bused and a few whites rode the bus. And one day my aunt was a bus driver, my Aunt Lillian, and she was a bus driver. And one day we got on the bus and she said, you can\'t have, you all can\'t sit in these first five seats. And I said, huh. This is my aunt never said. She said, no, say, I was told that the white kids had to sit up here and you all sit to the back. And, and of course I said, I don\'t, I don\'t agree with that. I say, this is, is over. This has been taken care of with desegregating the schools. And, and this is not real, you know, happening right now.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1536000,"end_time_ms":1584000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And she say, well, you need to talk to whomever. And I can remember, I\'ll never forget it\'s Mosley now. But that assistant principal came out there and he told us, and you going to first, he asked, well, who had something to say? I raised my hand, stood up and, and pretty much was asking, why is this the case? How, how can you designate somebody sit in the front and the blacks have to go to the back? And he told me, in no uncertain tone, you just sit down and shut up. Well, the next day I get to Black South, they called me in the office saying, I cursed him out, used profanity. Mind you. Now, he didn\'t know the woman behind the driver\'s wheel was my aunt, my daddy\'s baby sister. There\'s no way I\'m going curse in front of her uhhuh. I wouldn\'t say that I, I wouldn\'t possibly, but not in front of her.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1584000,"end_time_ms":1633000,"num_slots":1,"text":"He just lied, just flat out lied. John Gaines said, when you get on the bus, get in a seat. That\'s what he said he found, because the whole San Mateo was up in arms and was in his office crowded. And, and he, he said, Uhuh did. And then my mom said, now you saying that Sandy cursed you out. She said, now if you had said Regina did it, said, I would\'ve believed you said, but this one didn\'t curse you out like that. You know, he just lied, just flat out lied. He didn\'t like what I asked him. He said, if you had questions, raise your hand. I raised my hand. I stood up and was polite and asked him to explain why this is the case this day and age. And he, he told me to sit down and shut up.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":1633000,"end_time_ms":1637000,"num_slots":1,"text":"He didn\'t like that you were standing up for yourself. Mm-hmm. Yeah.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1637000,"end_time_ms":1711000,"num_slots":1,"text":"But other than that, those are the little things that stand out. But we made the, the, the most of it, the best of it. You know, you, you, you given lemons, you make lemonade. You just, you learn to do that. I told the kids, you know, all my life has been great. My parents took care of us, reared us, taught us the, the, the love of family, et cetera, all those things. But we saw some ugly things traveling up and down the road in, in the vehicles. My granddaddy would pull up and gas up at least four vehicles. The truck that carried the luggage, you know, the trunks with the clothing and the cooking wear in it. And a truck with, we called it a dog house with the house, like built on that. We rode in. He had a car and a pickup truck. Wow. He would gas \'em all up at the service station. But he, the people would tell us, the bathrooms are outta order. White patron pulls up, go in and use the restrooms that way, order. But we would go down the road, use the woods. Nobody fell in a ravine, no snakes, bit anybody. God took care of us. And so you, you learn to deal with what you got.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":1711000,"end_time_ms":1713000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Adapt. Yeah. Mm-hmm <affirmative>. Yeah.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1713000,"end_time_ms":1715000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Make do.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":1715000,"end_time_ms":1724000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And, uh, were there any, like, formalized threats or, um, sense of fear in the community? Instilled?","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1724000,"end_time_ms":1805000,"num_slots":1,"text":"No. San Mateo didn\'t. Uh, I have a friend that lives over here said he was threatened. You know, I don\'t know. He said because, because he was a good looking guy and popular. And he said some of the white girls liked him. But then that might\'ve been his ego talking. But anyway, uh, but as far as San Mateo, nah, nah, we didn\'t. And if they did, I didn\'t know about it or didn\'t hear about it. My family took care, took care of their business, you know. And it, it wasn\'t necessarily, uh, the schools being integrated. People just have views about people and, and, you know, uh, my brother, a cousin, two cousins, my brother, two cousins and, and a neighbor around the corner, they were arrested because chink, his real name is William. They call him Chink. He hollered at a white girl down the road from where we lived. And her parents called the cops. They came to the schools and arrested my brother and them. Wow. Yeah. So that kind, but it wasn\'t school, the integrating of the school. So, so it, you know, you know, it was there. You knew how people felt. And so you did the best you could to be who your parents rear reared you to be.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":1805000,"end_time_ms":1816000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And did you have any places outside the school and outside church where you found any community, any specific organizations?","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1816000,"end_time_ms":1862000,"num_slots":1,"text":"The, the only, I guess if Zeta Phi Beta Sorority, uh, it\'s a service sorority. I\'m now a member of it. They used to have what they call the Blue Review. And when, when you got in high school, you had to be in at least 11th grade. You were invited to the Blue Review and you got to dress up and go to that. They, they did little things that were, it was fundraising, but yet it was an opportunity for us to do something else. But no other clubs. Everything else we had and did in San Mateo, we came up with it. We, we climbed trees and made fors and playhouses and stuff. We entertained each other. We, we learned how to do that.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":1862000,"end_time_ms":1869000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And did most of your family and friends and the people you surrounded yourself with come from the church or from","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1869000,"end_time_ms":1881000,"num_slots":1,"text":"The church and the community lived right there in the community. Even this day, pretty much a close knit community. Those two churches are still there. And, you know,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":1881000,"end_time_ms":1884000,"num_slots":1,"text":"So. And is the rest of your family still living in the area or?","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1884000,"end_time_ms":1952000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Uh, the majority, my oldest brother lives in, um, Jacksonville. And my oldest sister lives in New Jersey. Oh, wow. Yeah. And again, she got connected up there for us going on the season. Her daughter married a young man from New Jersey, from Freehold, New Jersey. Mm-hmm <affirmative>. And so that\'s where she lives up there near her daughter. Yeah. So it, it\'s just, and then I have one uncle that has a dozen children, and they all still live in most, got quite a few of them out in Texas. Uh, Killeen, uh, well, McAllen and Killeen, Texas and so on. But the majority still live in the area. I have one brother lives here in Palka, my sister. \'cause there are three girls left and three boys. And, and the brother that lives down the street from me and another sister that lives down the street, most of us live right in the area. All Palka or Putnam County. Most the majority.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":1952000,"end_time_ms":1954000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And so you graduated from Palka South in","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1954000,"end_time_ms":1956000,"num_slots":1,"text":"From Palka South in 1971.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":1956000,"end_time_ms":1959000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Um, did you go straight to college?","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":1959000,"end_time_ms":2010000,"num_slots":1,"text":"No, I, I, I call it, I say I lost a year, but really I probably gained a year because I tried St. John\'s and St. John\'s, to me, honestly felt too much like pal the South did mm-hmm <affirmative>. When I walked in, you are the one and you, it, it just, and so for a year I worked with my daddy picking oranges and doing what I had to do to, to make ends meet. And that summer, miss Asia that you interviewed her sister Asia and I were picking oranges together. Both of us were, I was up the tree. She was on the ground. We decided, you know what, there\'s something else that we could be doing. And both of us went to Florida a and m the next fall together. Wow. And we graduated the same year. And we both pledged Zeta the same time. So.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2010000,"end_time_ms":2015000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And I\'m sure Florida a and m was very different experience than,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2015000,"end_time_ms":2063000,"num_slots":1,"text":"You know, it Yeah. I might\'ve had a few white instructors, but, you know, I, I was able to just be at an HBCU and just, you know, see more people like me that possibly may have come from background similar. That felt what I felt at the time. And, and then, then I went to, uh, UNF, university of North Florida. Mm-hmm <affirmative>. To get my, my first master, no, my second master\'s. \'cause I got my first one from a and m, my second master\'s. At that point, I was mature and grown. So I handled that myself. So I knew how to step out and do my own thing and, and people would gravitate or I would gravitate to them. And so, so it was okay. Yeah. Yeah. Different.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2063000,"end_time_ms":2065000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And what did you study in your undergraduate degree?","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2065000,"end_time_ms":2071000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Undergraduate was elementary education. So I\'m certified early childhood and elementary.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2071000,"end_time_ms":2072000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And your master\'s was","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2072000,"end_time_ms":2078000,"num_slots":1,"text":"In, master\'s was in, uh, education. The first one. The second one was in educational leadership.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2078000,"end_time_ms":2085000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Okay. Yeah. And then after you got your second master\'s, did you go straight into teaching or","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2085000,"end_time_ms":2117000,"num_slots":1,"text":"No? No, I taught while I was getting, I got my first, my BS and then I started teaching, then I went back and got my, my master\'s, first master\'s while I was still teaching. Mm. Okay. And then I decided that I, I\'m gonna try my hand at administration, but they, they told us you had to, you know, be in ED leadership, get that, and you had to pass what they call the <inaudible>, Florida Educational Leadership Exam or something like that in order to become mm-hmm <affirmative>. Yeah. So I taught for 17 years.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2117000,"end_time_ms":2119000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Where did you first teach at?","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2119000,"end_time_ms":2121000,"num_slots":1,"text":"At, uh, Kelly Smith Elementary School.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2121000,"end_time_ms":2122000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Where, what? Um,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2122000,"end_time_ms":2133000,"num_slots":1,"text":"It\'s, it\'s out on one, out on 20 on the way to Gainesville School that sits there on 20. How long did you sit there for? I was there for 17 years. Fifth grade. Wow. Yeah.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2133000,"end_time_ms":2135000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Wow. What subjects did you","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2135000,"end_time_ms":2137000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Teach? Everything except music and pe.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2137000,"end_time_ms":2140000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Mm. What was your experience like there?","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2140000,"end_time_ms":2143000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Great. It was great. I","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2143000,"end_time_ms":2145000,"num_slots":1,"text":"<laugh>","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2145000,"end_time_ms":2166000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Students now just come back and love on me. And I love on them <laugh>. I\'ve met babies of my former students. Uh, we laugh about it. Our school sup uh, our school board attorney is Charlie Douglas. I was his fifth grade teacher. Wow. And if you ask him, he\'ll tell you Miss gi, Ms. Gillard.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2166000,"end_time_ms":2200000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Makes sense. But by then, people were better understanding that color and race, even gender doesn\'t dictate the kind of person you are. Mm-hmm <affirmative>. And people would want their children in your classroom. You know, I had waiting lists to get in this gi Ya\'s room. And I\'m not boasting a bragging, it\'s just by the goodness of God that instead of taking what happened in my past and becoming bitter, it made me better.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2200000,"end_time_ms":2204000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And was the, this elementary school, was it primarily","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2204000,"end_time_ms":2238000,"num_slots":1,"text":"That was what we considered a white school. That was the elite school in Putnam County? Yes, it was. Yeah. The doctor\'s children went there. The, the, uh, broker\'s children went there, <laugh>, the really just children went Wow. There, the head coach\'s children went there. Yeah. Oh, it was an elite school. But what I was telling you was the assistant principal at, uh, black of South, which was Black Joe Green, his wife Kathleen B. Green was the principal there? Mm. She hired me.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2238000,"end_time_ms":2239000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Oh,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2239000,"end_time_ms":2243000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Okay. And I stayed there until I went into leadership.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2243000,"end_time_ms":2247000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Okay. So were most of your students white students? Yes. Oh, okay.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2247000,"end_time_ms":2264000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And, and I only knew that once a year we had to put how many blacks, how many whites, how many male, how many female. And I\'d have to actually look and count. That\'s the gospel truth, because I taught children.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2264000,"end_time_ms":2269000,"num_slots":1,"text":"So, so you didn\'t, there wasn\'t much tension going there. It was less,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2269000,"end_time_ms":2273000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Less tension. Oh my God, yes. Yes. Mm-hmm","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2273000,"end_time_ms":2278000,"num_slots":1,"text":"<affirmative>. And parents didn\'t make any qual about it? No. No.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2278000,"end_time_ms":2285000,"num_slots":1,"text":"I could tell your parents, Hey, they were deciding. Hey, I want my kid there. That\'s awesome.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2285000,"end_time_ms":2287000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Yeah. So what year, what year did you begin teaching","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2287000,"end_time_ms":2346000,"num_slots":1,"text":"There? I started teaching in 77. Um, Ms. Kathleen B. Green didn\'t tell me in so many words that she had hired me. I went to sub, uh, Ethel. Ethel Bryant was gonna be gone that week leading up to Easter. So she was there that Monday. And she had stuff laid out for me for that Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday, Friday. I had to come up with some stuff. I had to take care of the little Easter party <laugh>, because she had a second or third grade. I can\'t remember which one. And I\'ll never forget Ms. Kathleen, B Green, Ms. KB Green would come in to the room. I said, okay. She just making sure everything\'s, it was, it was right. Well, after that, they had a teacher\'s planning day. I\'m at home in my house, in the bed. And my daddy says, Sandy, Ms. Green is on the phone. I said, Ms. Green.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2346000,"end_time_ms":2379000,"num_slots":1,"text":"So I get up and I get the phone and I say, yes, ma\'am. She said, where are you supposed to be, Gil, y\'all, where are you supposed to be? I\'m saying, huh. She never said to me, you\'re hired. Yeah. I had gone for the interview and then I subbed. But she had never said, you are hired. This is your job. She say, you need to get here. I\'m trying to introduce you. And you, she didn\'t say it to me, you were hurt. Oh my God. So anyway, that\'s how I started. But you better bet I was never late, you know, once. Yeah. She,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2379000,"end_time_ms":2380000,"num_slots":1,"text":"She must be glad that she","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2380000,"end_time_ms":2426000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Ended up taking you. Oh, lemme tell you. I, I went to work. I perfect attendance was my goal. I mean, I needed to be there for my kids. And I\'ll never forget, I had gone to work that day. It was a Monday or Tuesday early week. And I was going down the hall like this with my kids. And they were straight in line and quiet. And she said, GI, what\'s wrong with you? And I say, my, she was a little woman. She was strong though, <laugh>. But, uh, I said, I\'m hurting at my side. I\'m just hurting. And she could see it in my face and she say, I\'m calling a sub you, you go home. And I, I was headed home. I got on that bridge and pain just went all through me. Anyway, long story short, I ended up having to have my appendix removed. <laugh>.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2426000,"end_time_ms":2428000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And so, and you were still in class","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2428000,"end_time_ms":2468000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Still trying to go to work. But, uh, no, they put me in the hospital. I\'m saying, but that day be, that day that she saw me and sent me home, it was probably occurring Uhhuh. And I, I just, I still believe in that. I still believe that nobody could do the job like I could do for my kids. \'cause I know my kids. And, and I just took pride in that. Even when I was working in the fields growing up, I never wanted to miss a day of work because I didn\'t wanna lose that money that that day would bring in. So, work ethic. Alright. Yeah. That\'s an awesome. Alright. Where are we? <laugh> with time? I don\'t wanna, I don\'t wanna,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2468000,"end_time_ms":2472000,"num_slots":1,"text":"We\'re we\'re still good. We got, we got about, we got like 20 minutes.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2472000,"end_time_ms":2474000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Well, let\'s","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2474000,"end_time_ms":2475000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Go faster. I\'m, I\'m,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2475000,"end_time_ms":2496000,"num_slots":1,"text":"I\'m, I\'m gonna stop. But it, it\'s, it\'s just, and and it\'s almost like not pulling the bandaid off a so, but it\'s almost like you\'re pulling the cover off some stuff. It happened and it\'s like, it\'s back there in my mind and mm-hmm <affirmative>. And this is bringing it to the forefront. Yeah. I mean, I didn\'t suppress it or anything. It\'s just life kept moving.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2496000,"end_time_ms":2506000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Yeah. Yeah. No memory. Mm-hmm <affirmative>. Is like, passes by. I, I, I\'m 19 and I can\'t remember things from eight years ago. <laugh> <laugh>,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2506000,"end_time_ms":2511000,"num_slots":1,"text":"You will, if you, if you ever call on the spot, you, you would, you would","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2511000,"end_time_ms":2521000,"num_slots":1,"text":"<laugh> and just to, uh, round it out. After you finished teaching at, uh, this elementary school, where did you move on to?","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2521000,"end_time_ms":2575000,"num_slots":1,"text":"I went to an elementary school as an assistant principal. And I was there for one year because the superintendent at that time was a female. Jerry Milosh. She wanted me at the high school. She felt like I could be a positive influence, you know, a mentor letting people, the chil students see somebody that looks like them, et cetera. Anyway, uh, I, um, she left me, I was there only one year and she brought me to Palatka High School, the biggest school in Putnam County. She brought me there as an assistant principal. And I was upset because she had initially told me, I\'m gonna let you make the decision. And I had decided to stay, even though it was a longer drive. And even though she told me I would be making at least $10,000 more, it was about the kids. I had fallen in love with them.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2575000,"end_time_ms":2624000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And Yeah. And so I didn\'t want to leave them. But anyway, she finally said, okay, I gotta, I gotta go back on my word. You gotta go. And she put me there. And so it was during the summer, just before the kids would return. And I was pouting just like any kid would. P <laugh> and Coach McCool, Jim McCool tried to befriend, be befriend me. He was the head football coach. And he said, what do you like doing? I said, I\'m gonna be a Monday night football announcer. He says, oh, you can announce football. And of course, I\'ve been doing it now ever since. I still, I announced still this last season. Oh my. I do jd, I love jd. \'cause they let me have my way up there, <laugh>. I get my jock jams, and I just have a great time. I make the kids feel good, even if they\'re close to the play, I call their names and say, you know, still doing it. But I","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2624000,"end_time_ms":2628000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Wish all schools did that. Yeah. Like, it creates the ambiance.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2628000,"end_time_ms":2656000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Yeah. Yeah. I, I just, I I still enjoy it, you know? Did it last, last year with the pandemic and stuff? Yeah. And my cousin Linda, she, her husband was an assistant, no, he was the head coach of JV until, and he passed. And so she stays up in the booth with me. She\'s my spotter. And so we just sit up there and visit and have fun and, and stay connected with the, with the children. Yeah. You know, with the youth.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2656000,"end_time_ms":2660000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Yeah. And after that, did you move anywhere else, or?","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2660000,"end_time_ms":2745000,"num_slots":1,"text":"No, from there, um, when I retired, uh, moved from Palka High. David Buckles became principal. I, I mean a, a superintendent. And he sent me out in West Putman to Interlochen, uh, to Price middle school. And I became principal. I was there for 13 years. Wow. Then another superintendent came along and he wasn\'t too pleased with me because I supported David Buckles in the election. And I supported David Buckles because David Buckle had been there, done that he had taught, coached, uh, had a degree. This superintendent, that one had no degree. Anyway, um, so he brought me into Palka to Beasley Middle School, a school that he felt like was gonna fail. And so he put me there for three years. So eventually that school closed. I finished out, uh, at the district office, uh, as a parent liaison. And that\'s, and then, so, so I retired in that position, but I retired at Palka High. Mm-hmm <affirmative>. I went back to Palka. I had my office there for about six months. And at the end of my six months when I was to retire, the date certain was, uh, March, uh, may, May 30th and 12 o\'clock, noon, I walked out and released balloons. And,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2745000,"end_time_ms":2747000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And what year was that?","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2747000,"end_time_ms":2765000,"num_slots":1,"text":"That was in, I ran for school board in 20, uh, 14, 16. Alright, I gotta get my dates together. <laugh>. Alright. It\'s 16 to 20 and then 20 to 24. So 2015. 2015.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2765000,"end_time_ms":2766000,"num_slots":1,"text":"2015.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2766000,"end_time_ms":2767000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Yes.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2767000,"end_time_ms":2768000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Well,","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2768000,"end_time_ms":2769000,"num_slots":1,"text":"I was done","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2769000,"end_time_ms":2770000,"num_slots":1,"text":"<laugh>.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2770000,"end_time_ms":2772000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And then I, I ran for school. You","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2772000,"end_time_ms":2773000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Gotta celebrate. Yeah.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2773000,"end_time_ms":2798000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Yeah. And then, then after that, it was like God had spoken to me and my father had just passed the 1st of May. I retired the 30th of May. And it was just so perfect. Like God had laid it out. I ran and I won. Wow. And then the second term, I told God I wanted to run again, but I didn\'t wanna have to campaign. And I didn\'t, I had no opponent.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2798000,"end_time_ms":2799000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Wow.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2799000,"end_time_ms":2806000,"num_slots":1,"text":"So he\'s important in my life. As a matter of fact, I mm-hmm <affirmative>. I am, I have a church. I\'m a pastor of a church down in Wallock.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2806000,"end_time_ms":2808000,"num_slots":1,"text":"What\'s it, what\'s the name?","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2808000,"end_time_ms":2813000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Uh, it\'s St. James a ME. It\'s still a ME like my home church. Oh yeah. Yes. Yes.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2813000,"end_time_ms":2814000,"num_slots":1,"text":"That\'s awesome.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2814000,"end_time_ms":2826000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And, and you have to go to school. They send you to their training, you know, but I grew up a ME so I knew the doctrine, apostles Cree, all of that stuff, but we had to go to school","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2826000,"end_time_ms":2830000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Two years. And you still have that sense of community that you had Oh, yeah. As a child with the","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2830000,"end_time_ms":2834000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Church. Yes, most definitely. It\'s crucial. Yeah. It is crucial.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2834000,"end_time_ms":2836000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And do you see it among the kids? Like you had it","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2836000,"end_time_ms":2868000,"num_slots":1,"text":"To No. No. It\'s, it\'s not as strong as it was when I grew up. Yeah. And, and, and it was so strong when I grew up that at Points East Lac and San Mateo would go at it. <laugh>, that\'s community. Yeah. <laugh>, you know, but then, you know, people change. You grow up. And when we got to ca we became one. And then it looks like somebody else was encroaching on that. Which, which was integration. Yeah.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2868000,"end_time_ms":2945000,"num_slots":1,"text":"And anyway, like I say, it, it, it\'s not as bad now in retrospect. It\'s what made it worse or what made it as hard with the parents mm-hmm <affirmative>. And more so yes, we had some black parents with some negative or racial, uh, built in things, but mm-hmm <affirmative>. The majority were the whites that did not want their children to go to school with black kids because they had heard this, that and the other. Yes. You know, these preconceived notions. But when the kids got together and they didn\'t see necessarily what they had been taught, I can remember, and we can wrap it up. Yeah. The Howard Theater, they have an article in today\'s paper about it. They\'re selling the seats. The Howard Theater, I can remember it sat on that, sat on that curb and it was upstairs and downstairs. The whites went downstairs. The blacks had to go up in the balcony. Mm-hmm <affirmative>. So crazy. Yep. Dr. Knight, white doctor, he had a black waiting room and a white waiting, waiting room. Cynthia and I laughed about that last night, but it was the same doctor that took care of you. Took care of me. Yeah. It\'s just, it was just people not wanting to let go. Not","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2945000,"end_time_ms":2947000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Very symbolic. Yeah.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2947000,"end_time_ms":2950000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Yeah. So anyway.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2950000,"end_time_ms":2963000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Yeah. And then my last question, and you can say, uh, you can keep it as brief as you want. Okay. It\'s just, um, is there anything that, any advice you have to current educators with our education","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2963000,"end_time_ms":2973000,"num_slots":1,"text":"System? Oh, oh yeah. Oh yeah. Yeah. My advice to them would be, first know that you are called to teach.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":2973000,"end_time_ms":2974000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Yeah.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":2974000,"end_time_ms":3017000,"num_slots":1,"text":"I believe that it is a calling. When I went to a and m, they had a program called Early Intervention and you got no credit for it. We had to put in 18 to 20 hours. Wow. Volunteering in, uh, an elementary setting, be at a daycare. It had to be. And you went, they said, because they did not want someone to graduate from there. And it dawned on them, Hey, I don\'t want anything to do with children. It was early intervention. You deciding. So I would say to any educators now, number one, make sure you are called, you know, that\'s your passion. You get excited about it and then love the children and the rest will fall into place. Just","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":3017000,"end_time_ms":3018000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Come to you.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S2","tier":"Speaker 3","start_time_ms":3018000,"end_time_ms":3032000,"num_slots":1,"text":"Yep. It will, it\'ll happen if you love the children, children, period. It doesn\'t matter who they are, what they smell like, where they came from. Just love the children and you can get past anything. Yep.","dependents":[]},{"speaker":"S1","tier":"Speaker 2","start_time_ms":3032000,"end_time_ms":3035000,"num_slots":1,"text":"I think that\'s a wonderful way to end the end, the interview. Okay. All right. Uh, let me see how to turn this off here.","dependents":[]}]}')}}]);
